1
00:00:00,700 --> 00:00:08,080
From VOA Learning English, this is the Health & Lifestyle report.

2
00:00:07,940 --> 00:00:18,960
At Myosin Marketing in Austin, Texas, the group employee meeting begins with an uncommon activity for a workplace.

3
00:00:18,860 --> 00:00:30,320
The members gather on Zoom and the head of the company, Sean Clayton, leads them through a deep-breathing exercise.

4
00:00:29,960 --> 00:00:39,740
Clayton says the activity helps his employees relax and to be willing to take creative risks.

5
00:00:39,589 --> 00:00:48,830
“At first they thought it was really weird,” he said, adding that most people turned off their cameras.

6
00:00:48,540 --> 00:00:53,920
But, after a couple of weeks, there was a change.

7
00:00:53,800 --> 00:00:58,100
The employees said the deep breathing felt good.

8
00:00:57,400 --> 00:01:08,720
Studies show that deep breathing can be an effective way to reduce tension, or stress, at work.

9
00:01:08,540 --> 00:01:13,260
But people may not think about their breathing while on the job.

10
00:01:12,720 --> 00:01:24,540
Workers who sit at computers for long periods tend to take shallow breaths as their shoulders slowly rise.

11
00:01:23,780 --> 00:01:37,540
Workers who spend the day on their feet in retail or health care may be too busy to center their attention on breathing.

12
00:01:37,400 --> 00:01:44,940
But there is good reason to stop what you are doing and take deep breaths, research suggests.

13
00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:51,940
Long-lasting stress can increase the risk of heart disease and stroke.

14
00:01:51,440 --> 00:02:01,140
Experts at the American Heart Association say it can be as harmful as secondhand smoke.

15
00:02:00,640 --> 00:02:14,040
Research suggests deep-breathing exercises can lower a person’s blood pressure and reduce anxiety.

16
00:02:13,769 --> 00:02:17,720
There are many benefits to deep breathing.

17
00:02:17,500 --> 00:02:20,340
For starters, it is free.

18
00:02:20,300 --> 00:02:23,420
It can be done anywhere.

19
00:02:22,740 --> 00:02:33,040
And unlike a 30-minute meditation practice, most deep breathing exercises do not take much time.

20
00:02:31,340 --> 00:02:39,220
Also, it gives you something to focus on – your breathing.

21
00:02:38,760 --> 00:02:43,580
Experts say that this can help to calm racing thoughts.

22
00:02:43,080 --> 00:03:00,920
Focusing on breathing for one to five minutes can help you clear your mind and let you “get back to focusing on the one thing you want to accomplish,” said Glenn Levine.

23
00:03:00,760 --> 00:03:11,080
He is a heart and blood system doctor and professor at Baylor College of Medicine in Houston, Texas.

24
00:03:11,000 --> 00:03:16,190
A good way to do deep breathing exercises is outside, Levine said.

25
00:03:15,800 --> 00:03:22,500
However, if that is not possible, doing them at a desk works.

26
00:03:22,040 --> 00:03:35,300
“Instead of focusing on the screen or work, just focus on your breathing. If possible,” Levine said, “close your eyes.”

27
00:03:34,140 --> 00:03:44,200
Even very busy people can find time for daily breathing exercises.

28
00:03:43,760 --> 00:03:51,140
Lisa Marie Deleveaux is a marketing professional and mother of five.

29
00:03:50,960 --> 00:03:57,500
She lost her job several months ago and has struggled to find a new one.

30
00:03:57,040 --> 00:04:07,760
Deleveaux wakes early most mornings before her children, to do breathing exercises.

31
00:04:07,560 --> 00:04:13,820
“If you set a priority for yourself ... you can make the time,” Deleveaux said.

32
00:04:13,240 --> 00:04:24,460
With one breathing exercise, she breaths in through one nostril and then out through the other.

33
00:04:24,280 --> 00:04:33,180
She uses a thumb or forefinger to hold one nostril closed at a time.

34
00:04:32,980 --> 00:04:45,060
“It relaxes my mind. It makes my mind so full of ease. It brings you back to the present moment,” she added.

35
00:04:44,870 --> 00:05:03,520
To get ahead of anxiety before starting her workday, sales representative Lindsay Carlisle of Michigan does breathing exercises with her seven-year-old daughter during their drive to school.

36
00:05:03,360 --> 00:05:13,660
They breathe in for seven counts, hold their breath for five, and then breathe out for seven counts.

37
00:05:13,480 --> 00:05:16,120
They repeat this several times.

38
00:05:15,380 --> 00:05:26,780
“Throughout that process, my shoulders start to drop on their own, and it really is calming,” Carlisle said.

39
00:05:26,240 --> 00:05:39,780
Suze Yalof Schwartz was an overworked magazine editor when her mother-in-law taught her a three-minute meditation method.

40
00:05:39,390 --> 00:05:43,720
Yalof Schwartz says it changed her life.

41
00:05:43,520 --> 00:05:59,100
She left her career and founded Unplug Meditation, a Santa Monica, California, company with a meditation studio, an app, and programs for corporate customers.

42
00:05:58,820 --> 00:06:08,740
“When we slow down our breath, we send a signal to our brain that everything’s OK, even when it’s not,” she said.

43
00:06:08,420 --> 00:06:17,260
Another 16-second breathing exercise is called box breathing.

44
00:06:17,200 --> 00:06:26,940
You breathe in for four counts, hold for four, breathe out for four counts and hold for another four.

45
00:06:26,540 --> 00:06:38,740
Yalof Schwartz has taught it to people in stressful jobs including firefighters, police and doctors.

46
00:06:38,580 --> 00:06:57,840
“It is the best thing that you can do at work before you have a meeting, before you send out an email that you wish you didn’t send, before you have a difficult conversation, because it just calms you down, gets rid of your negative energy,” she said.

47
00:06:57,560 --> 00:07:12,240
Employers such as Coca-Cola, Mattel and Netflix have used Unplug Meditation to teach breathing or meditation.

48
00:07:12,180 --> 00:07:19,990
It is not always easy for workers to find space for deep breathing exercises.

49
00:07:19,880 --> 00:07:28,000
For example, salespeople often work alongside their customers.

50
00:07:27,320 --> 00:07:36,800
Yalof Schwartz suggests doing breathing exercises when making a sale or organizing items.

51
00:07:36,140 --> 00:07:47,400
Carlisle, the sales representative, sets a timer on her phone telling her to breathe deeply.

52
00:07:47,240 --> 00:07:54,930
She also keeps a note near her computer that simply says “Breathe.”

53
00:07:54,800 --> 00:08:10,850
“The anxiety is always going to be there,” Carlisle said. “But at least I know I have one small tool. ... It sounds so simple and silly, but it works.”

54
00:08:10,720 --> 00:08:13,940
And that’s the Health & Lifestyle report.

55
00:08:13,780 --> 00:08:17,120
I’m Anna Matteo. And I’m Mario Ritter, Jr.
